               <table xmlns="" width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
                  <tr>
                     <td width="15%" class="TableCell" valign="top"><b>Question:</b><br><a href="http://www.earthdawn-classic.com/faqs/selectTopic.html;jsessionid=a0h_bmGHGcIb?id=203974">Earthdawn Players Compendium FAQ</a><br>
                        	      Last Updated By Richard Vowles on 1/1/06
                     </td>
                     <td width="1%" class="TableCell"><img src="/images/spacer.gif" border="0"></td>
                     <td width="84%" class="TableCell"><b>
                           How should I apply modifiers? I mean, what in what types of situations should I apply a modifier to a roll versus modifying
                           the difficulty number versus increasing the required success level? I would imagine the first would be for modifiers that
                           affect the character personally, the second would be for modifiers that actually change the nature of the task, and the third
                           would be when you need to use an ability in a very specific or demanding manner.
                           </b></td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="15%" class="TableCellAlternate" valign="top"><b>Answer:</b></td>
                     <td width="1%" class="TableCellAlternate"><img src="/images/spacer.gif" border="0"></td>
                     <td width="84%" class="TableCellAlternate">
                        There is a description of this in the forthcoming Gamemaster's Compendium, but it ultimatly boils down to this:<br /><br />Use
                        different Result Levels when a task becomes significantly harder, and use smaller modifiers for fine-tuning (Result Levels
                        just increase the DN by a fixed amount, individual modifiers don't). All of this applies to Difficulty Numbers, bonuses and
                        pernalties to a test result are usually determined by the system itself.
                        
                     </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="100%" colspan="3" class="TableCellAlternate">
                        <hr>
                     </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="15%" class="TableCell" valign="top"><b>Question:</b><br><a href="http://www.earthdawn-classic.com/faqs/selectTopic.html;jsessionid=a0h_bmGHGcIb?id=203974">Earthdawn Players Compendium FAQ</a><br>
                        	      Last Updated By Richard Vowles on 1/1/06
                     </td>
                     <td width="1%" class="TableCell"><img src="/images/spacer.gif" border="0"></td>
                     <td width="84%" class="TableCell"><b>
                           The description for physical defense says it represents a character's ability to dodge a blow. Would it matter in any of the
                           rules if I described hits that didn't get past a targer's PD as being dodged, blocked, or parried? I know there is a riposte
                           talent and skill, but I think it's odd that a warrior wouldn't know how to block or parry until higher circles.
                           </b></td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="15%" class="TableCellAlternate" valign="top"><b>Answer:</b></td>
                     <td width="1%" class="TableCellAlternate"><img src="/images/spacer.gif" border="0"></td>
                     <td width="84%" class="TableCellAlternate">
                        It doesn't really matter, although I personally tend to describe the miss in a way that the attacker did something wrong.
                        There is always a chance of overusing this, so the descriptions should never be the same.
                        
                     </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="100%" colspan="3" class="TableCellAlternate">
                        <hr>
                     </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="15%" class="TableCell" valign="top"><b>Question:</b><br><a href="http://www.earthdawn-classic.com/faqs/selectTopic.html;jsessionid=a0h_bmGHGcIb?id=203974">Earthdawn Players Compendium FAQ</a><br>
                        	      Last Updated By Richard Vowles on 1/1/06
                     </td>
                     <td width="1%" class="TableCell"><img src="/images/spacer.gif" border="0"></td>
                     <td width="84%" class="TableCell"><b>
                           Concerning the rule of three, are you only allowed one &quot;boost&quot; within<br />each source? For over-lapping durations,
                           is it whatever comes first or the strongest?
                           </b></td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="15%" class="TableCellAlternate" valign="top"><b>Answer:</b></td>
                     <td width="1%" class="TableCellAlternate"><img src="/images/spacer.gif" border="0"></td>
                     <td width="84%" class="TableCellAlternate">
                        Pick the three sources that are most beneficial to the character or let him decide. In my opinon, the 'one or more' implies
                        that you can have three spell bonuses, or two spell and one talent bonus etc - as long as the total is three. Keep in mind
                        that bonuses to a single characteristic or Attribute are usually not cumulative, so this is easier to handle than it might
                        appear.
                        
                     </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="100%" colspan="3" class="TableCellAlternate">
                        <hr>
                     </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="15%" class="TableCell" valign="top"><b>Question:</b><br><a href="http://www.earthdawn-classic.com/faqs/selectTopic.html;jsessionid=a0h_bmGHGcIb?id=203974">Earthdawn Players Compendium FAQ</a><br>
                        	      Last Updated By Richard Vowles on 1/1/06
                     </td>
                     <td width="1%" class="TableCell"><img src="/images/spacer.gif" border="0"></td>
                     <td width="84%" class="TableCell"><b>
                           (pg. 29) - How was Parlainth returned?
                           </b></td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="15%" class="TableCellAlternate" valign="top"><b>Answer:</b></td>
                     <td width="1%" class="TableCellAlternate"><img src="/images/spacer.gif" border="0"></td>
                     <td width="84%" class="TableCellAlternate">
                        This was the topic of the first Earthdawn novel, The Longing Ring. We hope to re-publish it somewhere in the future. The Parlainth
                        Boxed Set also has the full history, and we will release that one as part of our Earthdawn line in a revised format. That's
                        not answering your question, I know, but I fear that would take me too many words at this stage.<br /><br /><a href="http://www.stiggybaby.com"
                        target="_blank">StiggyBaby</a> still has the old FASA stock of The Longing Ring (along with the other ED books).
                        
                     </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="100%" colspan="3" class="TableCellAlternate">
                        <hr>
                     </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="15%" class="TableCell" valign="top"><b>Question:</b><br><a href="http://www.earthdawn-classic.com/faqs/selectTopic.html;jsessionid=a0h_bmGHGcIb?id=203974">Earthdawn Players Compendium FAQ</a><br>
                        	      Last Updated By Richard Vowles on 1/1/06
                     </td>
                     <td width="1%" class="TableCell"><img src="/images/spacer.gif" border="0"></td>
                     <td width="84%" class="TableCell"><b>
                           In the text for Starting Spells, you say a first circle character can only have First Circle spells in a matrix. What if he
                           has higher ranks in his matrices though?
                           </b></td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="15%" class="TableCellAlternate" valign="top"><b>Answer:</b></td>
                     <td width="1%" class="TableCellAlternate"><img src="/images/spacer.gif" border="0"></td>
                     <td width="84%" class="TableCellAlternate">
                        He can have higher ranks, but he lacks the understanding to put spells higher than his current Circle in his matrices. The
                        Spell Magic chapter will shed some more light on this. If a character has spells higher than his current Circle, he can only
                        cast them using Raw Magic or by casting directly from his Grimoire.
                        
                     </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="100%" colspan="3" class="TableCellAlternate">
                        <hr>
                     </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="15%" class="TableCell" valign="top"><b>Question:</b><br><a href="http://www.earthdawn-classic.com/faqs/selectTopic.html;jsessionid=a0h_bmGHGcIb?id=203974">Earthdawn Players Compendium FAQ</a><br>
                        	      Last Updated By Dammi on 1/2/06
                     </td>
                     <td width="1%" class="TableCell"><img src="/images/spacer.gif" border="0"></td>
                     <td width="84%" class="TableCell"><b>
                           (pg. 214) - Why are the costs for talent knacks so much more expensive in your new rules?
                           </b></td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="15%" class="TableCellAlternate" valign="top"><b>Answer:</b></td>
                     <td width="1%" class="TableCellAlternate"><img src="/images/spacer.gif" border="0"></td>
                     <td width="84%" class="TableCellAlternate">
                        The old costs were a joke - we could have dropped the costs entirely. We wanted Talent Knacks worth more consideration.
                        
                     </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="100%" colspan="3" class="TableCellAlternate">
                        <hr>
                     </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="15%" class="TableCell" valign="top"><b>Question:</b><br><a href="http://www.earthdawn-classic.com/faqs/selectTopic.html;jsessionid=a0h_bmGHGcIb?id=203974">Earthdawn Players Compendium FAQ</a><br>
                        	      Last Updated By Dammi on 1/2/06
                     </td>
                     <td width="1%" class="TableCell"><img src="/images/spacer.gif" border="0"></td>
                     <td width="84%" class="TableCell"><b>
                           (pg. 231) - It seems weird that an adept with an attribute only Karma capability can use it when defaulting a skill but not
                           when he actually has ranks in the skill.
                           </b></td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="15%" class="TableCellAlternate" valign="top"><b>Answer:</b></td>
                     <td width="1%" class="TableCellAlternate"><img src="/images/spacer.gif" border="0"></td>
                     <td width="84%" class="TableCellAlternate">
                        Use of an Attribute invokes the magic of his Discipline, which basically supports him in a intuitive way. By learning a skill,
                        he usually learns things not supported by his Discipline and cannot use Karma. However, once he learns a rank, he succeeds
                        at an Average result.
                        
                     </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                     <td width="100%" colspan="3" class="TableCellAlternate">
                        <hr>
                     </td>
                  </tr>
